The anhydrous ammonia manual has sections that include procedures for the following:

* Inspecting valves and equipment;

* Testing valves and equipment;

* Calibrating equipment and alarms;

* Unloading ammonia from a delivery truck to Tank 2 (T-2);

* Evacuating lines containing anhydrous ammonia;

* Isolating valves and equipment for maintenance;

* Alarm response; and

* EHS expectations.

The detailed procedures for unloading ammonia from the delivery truck to T-2 contain the following elements:

* Steps for ensuring that the load of ammonia is appropriate in both volume and product quality;

* Steps for ensuring that all safety issues are addressed, including worker protection and the location of emergency equipment;

* Preparatory steps that are designed to ensure safe off-loading of ammonia from the truck;

* Responsibilities of workers during off-loading, such as monitoring for leaks, spills, and carefully watching the T-2 levels for possible overfilling; and

* Steps to take following completion of ammonia off-loading.

Copies of the manuals that cover the anhydrous ammonia system are kept in the control room for easy access to the operator at all times.

Management is expected to provide an environment that allows risks to be managed.  They are also expected to manage performance through positive reinforcement.  Obvious and intentional violations of safety policies and standards must not be tolerated and will result in disciplinary action.

Managers must:

* Know and manage employee capabilities;

* Ensure proper resources are available to do each job; and

* Address training needs and ensure employees have been properly trained to perform their jobs safely; the employee is an equal driver in this and on occasion may need to be the primary driver.

In addition to the duties listed above, Plant management must:

* Set, communicate, and clarify expectations;

* Consider safety and the health of people first when making demands on site reso

urces (capital, people, time, etc.);

* Use appropriate safety recognition and disciplinary action;

* Identify, coordinate, and communicate performance/compliance measurements of the employees and their progress;

* Involve the appropriate functions in equipment layout, design, Standard Operating Procedures (SOPs), training, etc.;

* Ensure that the appropriate operating discipline is in place and the property MOC documentation is practiced and understood; and

* Ensure root cause investigations and analysis are performed when trigger criteria are met.



1.3   FACILITY DESCRIPTION AND REGULATED SUBSTANCES INFORMATION



1.3.1       Description of Stationary Sources

Calpine acquired CPPP from The Dow Chemical Company (?Dow?) in July 1998.  Calpine sells electricity to Dow and to Pacific Gas and Electric Company (PG&E). In addition, the Plant sells steam to Dow and to USSPOSCO Industries? nearby steel mill. 

1.3.2    Description of the Ammonia Storage System

The Plant is regulated under the Clean Air Act Amendments, also referred to as the federal RMP and the CalARP Program, due to on-site ammonia storage in excess of the 10,000-pound RMP applicability threshold in a process. The legal authority for the federal RMP program is Title 40 of the Code of Federal Regulations (CFR), Part 68. The legal authority for the CalARP Program is the California Health and Safety Code (H&SC), Division 20, Chapter 6.95, Article 2 (commencing with Section 25531). The California Office of Emergency Services has issued implementation regulations under Title 19 of the California Code of Regulations (CCR), Division 2, Chapter 4.5.  

The Plant?s CalARP-covered process is the ammonia storage system that provides an ammonia source for the Selective Catalytic Reduction (SCR) system (stationary source). The SCR unit is required to control air emissions.  The stationary source-covered process consists of one 15,000gallon tank storing a maximum of 12,750 gallons (72,548 pounds) [United States Env

dustry authorities: 

* The Occupational Safety and Health Administration?s (OSHA?s) 29 CFR 1910.111 Storage and Handling of Anhydrous Ammonia standard;

* ANSI safety requirements for the storage and handling of anhydrous ammonia; and

* Standards Association of Australia (SAA) Anhydrous Ammonia Code.

The Plant is dedicated to protecting employees, the community, and the environment from chemical incidents through safe operation of the facility.   To ensure efficient and effective management of Plant operations, management has developed the PSM program and RMP.  These programs provide a systematic and integrated approach to evaluating, implementing, and continuously improving PSM/RMP activities.  The manuals for these programs maintained at the Plant address how to implement the various ongoing activities (e.g., process design and maintenance, training, control of contractors, operating procedures, emergency response planning) that impact covered processes.  This approach also ensures the participation of management and staff.  Detailed descriptions of program implementation, such as for training are presented in Section 1.4.5.

The Plant Manager has overall responsibility for the development, implementation, and integration of PSM/RMP program elements.  One covered process is present at the Plant and has been identified based on federal and state PSM/RMP regulations. 

 The Plant Manager?s responsibilities include:

* Overall responsibility for the development, implementation, and integration of the PSM/RMP program elements;

* Monitoring follow-up/documentation of Process Hazard Analysis (PHA) records

* Reviewing the Management of Change form;

* Participating in pre-startup safety review;

* Organizing and directing Incident Investigation Teams;

* Overseeing implementation of corrective measures on incident investigation;

* Reviewing PSM audits, ensuring that audits are performed and deficiencies corrected;

* Ensuring employee involvement in the development

 and revision of Operating Procedures;

* Participating on the PSM Committee;

* Participating in Incident Investigation.

Other managers at the Plant conduct activities that are indirectly related to PSM/RMP.  These include the roles and responsibilities listed below.

Department Engineer responsibilities include:

* Overseeing development of chemical process technology and process equipment design information;

* Maintaining and updating process technology and process equipment information;

* Reviewing MOC form and approving new or modified equipment;

* Participating in and certifying pre-startup safety reviews;

* Overseeing and updating piping and instrumentation diagrams (P&IDs) and engineering drawings;

* Ensuring that new process safety information is incorporated into training information; and

* Participating on the PSM Committee.

Maintenance Manager responsibilities include:

* Maintaining Mechanical Integrity maintenance management system;

* Developing training on new/modified Mechanical Integrity procedures (with the Compliance Manager);

* Assigning and overseeing equipment maintenance;

* Identifying maintenance training;

* Supervising the Hot Work Permit process;

* Overseeing equipment maintenance and inspections;

* Developing process equipment information; and

* Reviewing MOC form.

Compliance Manager responsibilities include:

* Develop, track, and oversee the site safety training program;

* Develop and exercise the Emergency Action Plan;

* Coordinate with public responders;

* Develop accident investigation procedures;

* Oversee compliance audits;

* Develop employee participation plans;

* Maintaining contractor injury and illness logs;

* Revise and develop procedures and guidelines to meet RMP regulations; and

* Manage RMP documentation



